a comparative evaluation of versions of basic.wfrom its inception, the basic language hasgrown in terms of its usage, scope of usage, and its features.  this article compares ten of the currentversions of basic with each other, with two earlier versions, and with the proposed standard for minimalbasic. the comparison is arranged by the features of the versions and by computational comparisonof computation and times and processing costs.cacm april, lientz, b. p..kbasic, interpretive language summary.c. .ca jb january ,   : pm